Section1.Para:
When a cylinder layer substance possesses gyrotropy (magnetize ferrite or/and semiconductor) then the substance properties are described by tensors of the permeability
$\hat{\mu}$ or/and the permittivity
$\hat{\varepsilon}$ in the Cartesian coordinates in the form: 1
$$  egin{aligned} \hat{\mu} &= \left(  egin{array}{c@{\quad}c@{\quad}c} 1 + \chi_{\mu} & \mathrm{i}
u _{\mu} & 0 \ - \mathrm{i}
u_{\mu} & 1 + \chi_{\mu} & 0 \ 0 & 0 & \mu_{p} \end{array} ight), \ \hat{\varepsilon} &= \left(  egin{array}{c@{\quad}c@{\quad}c} 1 + \chi_{\varepsilon} & \mathrm{i}
u_{\varepsilon} & 0 \ - \mathrm{i}
u_{\varepsilon} & 1 + \chi_{\varepsilon} & 0 \ 0 & 0 & \varepsilon_{p} \end{array} ight). \end{aligned} $$ The solution of the Maxwell equations cannot be expressed through the superposition of TE and TM waves in general case, i.e. when the material of cylinder layer is described by one of tensors (1) or both ones (1), as well as the incident EM wave propagation is not perpendicular to the cylindrical axis, i.e. the incidence angle θ≠90∘. Below we are going to present in detail the new method of the Maxwell equation solution for the general case of the scattering problem which is more complicated than partial ones.
